Seems like a lot of trouble to go thru, but it is a fun gun, with rimfire power and NOT a firearm. Every gun enthusist should have at least one PCP, this one is a dandy with power to drop a coyote. title: For Sale:  *SALE PENDING* Husqvarna m1907 System Browning .380acp *SHIPPING AVAILABLE TO YOUR FFL*
postcontent: Up for sale is a Husqvarna M1907 in .380 acp. These have become scarce in recent years, especially in this condition!  It comes with 3 magazines and the original holster. I'll also throw in 65 rounds of .380 acp target loads if purchased locally.  I have fired this pistol and it shoots extremely well and functioned flawlessly.  I had plans to modify it, refinish it, and use it as a concealed carry gun, but its in too nice of condition to mess with it. This pistol was designed by John Moses Browning, the inventor of such firearms as the 1903 Colt Pocket Hammerless and m1911, which is why it looks similar in design.  Originally these were made by FN in Belgium and called the m1903, then after the Germans occupied Belgium during WWI, Husqvarna in Sweden picked up production in 1917.  This one is in one of the finest conditions I've ever seen with all number matching (including all small parts), original finish, original lanyard ring (these are often missing), and appears to have been made in the early 20s according to its 4 digit serial number. The frame also has markings indicating it was issued to the 9th Infantry Regiment and was gun number 323.  The m1907 is very similar to the 1903 Colt Pocket Hammerless, but parts and magazines will not interchange.  Magazines and the majority of parts should interchange with the original FN version though.  The m1907 has a larger frame, longer slide and barrel, and features a last round hold open thanks to the design of the magazine and the added lever on the side of the frame.  Originally these were chambered for the 9mm Browning Long, but were converted to .380acp when they were imported into the U.S. by pressing an insert into the chamber of the barrel.  Original barrels can be found online for as cheap as $20 if you desire to shoot the original 9mm Browning long round.  Please, no tire kickers. I won't waste your time, don't waste mine. I've been burned too many times in the past by holding items for people who change their mind and don't have the common courtesy to notify me, so first come/ first serve. I prefer face to face, but I'm willing to ship to your FFL for $45. I'm also willing to travel up to 45 minutes away to meet with a buyer.
